[1]
Date: Tue 7 Jan 2003 [edited]
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@derwent.co.uk>
Source: Malay Mail (Malaysia), Tue 7 Jan 2003 [edited]
<http://www.emedia.com.my/Current_News/MM/Tuesday/National/20030107093045>

Malaysia: Selangor has the most cases in nation
-----------------------------------------------
The Selangor government is shifting its focus to the public to check the
dengue situation, as the state [of Selangor] has the largest number of
cases in the country. Public apathy towards the environment has been
identified as one of the main causes, said state executive councillor in
charge of health Datuk Tang See Hang. "It is the tidak apa [meaning,
variously, "no problem", "don't worry", or the "whatever" ubiquitous in the
United States] attitude. This must change," he said. He took the people to
task for not doing their part to keep the environment clean. Tang made the
comments after chairing a press conference on the state's dengue situation
at the Ampang Jaya Municipal Council in Pandan Indah yesterday.
A total of 9385 cases with 17 deaths had been reported in Selangor, as of
28 Dec 2002. A total of 29 615 cases had been reported in the country as of
14 Dec 2002. It was reported that there were 54 fatalities nationwide last
year. "This is the worst year when compared to the past 10 years, with the
figure increasing every year since then," said Tang. He said there was no
need to put the state on a "dengue alert" as they had an action plan. Tang
declined to elaborate on the plan, however, except to say that it included
educational programmes, fogging, awareness campaigns, and the participation
of the public and non-governmental organizations. "Our action plan will be
introduced immediately by the local authorities and the State Action
Committee on Dengue 2003 set up to address the problem."
On why Selangor had the largest number of cases in the nation, he said it
was also due to high population density and inconsistent weather. "It rains
on some days while it is dry on others. It is also partly caused by rapid
development and some construction projects," Tang said. "Houses situated
close to one other and movement of the people are the other factors."
It was reported that there were 4 cases in the Selayang Municipal Council
(MPS) jurisdiction and district of Gombak, 3 in the Sepang district, and 3
within the boundary of Subang Jaya Municipal Council.
--
