Source: Daily Post (Fiji), Wed 8 Jan 2003 [edited]
<http://www.fijilive.com/news/news.php3?art=08/08z10.htm>

Fiji: dengue virus type 1 outbreak in Suva and Lautoka
------------------------------------------------------
The Ministry of Health has confirmed an outbreak of dengue virus type 1 in
specific areas in Suva and Lautoka. Acting health permanent secretary Dr
Timaima Tuiketei said that, in the past few days, an outbreak in Suva has
seen 16 dengue cases reported from CWM (Colonial War Memorial) hospital and
Suva private hospital. She said the regions affected in Suva are mainly
within the Grantham Road-Laucala Bay road, [and]
Nasinu-Caubati-Narere-Nakasi areas. "The other areas in Fiji are still
under a dengue alert warning, and everyone should take heed of this caution."
Dr Tuiketei said the Ministry of Health has activated its dengue outbreak
task force with an action plan to respond and monitor the situation. These
include:
press releases with continuing public update on dengue outbreak information;
active community mobilization [...to...] strengthen clean-up campaigns with
localized spraying of identified affected areas;
strengthening of health promotion and dengue awareness messages in TV,
newspapers, and public radio broadcasts;
utilization of the Dengue Clinical Management guidelines for health personnel;
ongoing surveillance and monitoring of cases within [local] health services;
localized spraying in Suva areas commencing today, and next week a second
round of spraying in the identified areas in Lautoka and Labasa.
Dr Tuiketei said the government is providing FJD 40 000 [USD 19 860]
initially for these dengue outbreak activities. She said the World Health
Organization is asking everyone to clean up their own household and
compounds, workplaces, schools, and other areas in the community and
destroy all the potential mosquito breeding places and sources. "This is
everyone's responsibility, hence, we need to stop this dengue outbreak.
Collectively we can put a stop the outbreak."
The Ministry of Health has put out a dengue alert warning to all health
personnel and health facilities, all town and city councils, all rural
local authorities, and the public at large to strengthen the dengue
prevention awareness and control activities.
A total of 117 dengue cases were confirmed in 2002.
